__NOTOC__
The [[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar Convention on Wetlands]] is an international [[treaty]] for the conservation and sustainable utilization of [[wetland]]s,<ref name=ramsar>{{cite web | url=http://www.ramsar.org/cda/ramsar/display/main/main.jsp?zn=ramsar&cp=1_4000_0__ | title=The Ramsar Convention on Wetlands | accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref> i.e., to stem the progressive encroachment on and loss of wetlands now and in the future, recognizing the fundamental [[Ecology|ecological]] functions of wetlands and their economic, cultural, scientific, and recreational value.<ref name="Ramsar list">{{cite web|title=Ramsar List|url=http://www.ramsar.org/pdf/sitelist.pdf|publisher=Ramsar.org|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref>  Since the convention became effective in Poland on 22 March 1978, the designation of Wetland of International Importance has been applied to thirteen locations in the country, which combine to form an area of {{convert|145075|ha|acre|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing">{{cite web|title=Ramsar Briefing Notes - Poland|url=http://www.ramsar.org/cda/en/ramsar-pubs-notes-annotated-ramsar-16086/main/ramsar/1-30-168%5E16086_4000_0__|publisher=Ramsar.org|accessdate=31 March 2013}}</ref><ref name="RSP">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bh66tgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y | title=Ramsar sites in Poland | publisher=Institute of Environmental Protection | author=Sienkiewicz, Jadwiga | year=2008 | location=Warsaw | page=70 | isbn=83-60312-85-0}}</ref>

==Sites==
*''(Site 756)''&nbsp;'''[[Biebrza National Park]]''', [[Podlaskie Voivodeship]], {{convert|592|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
The site consists of a series of [[temperate zone]] forested and non-forested [[bog]]s that provide a variety of habitats for birds, mammals, fish and plants.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing" /> The available habitats are ecologically typical of a [[Riparian zone|riparian area]] including [[swamps]] and [[Tussock (grass)|tussocks]] separated from [[Agriculture|cultivated areas]] by black alder ({{lang-lat|[[Alnus glutinosa]]}}) and white willow ({{lang-lat|[[Salix alba]]}}) forested areas.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing" /><ref name="RSP"/>

*''(Site 1563)''&nbsp;'''[[Drużno Lake|Drużno Lake Nature Reserve]]''', [[Warmian-Masurian Voivodeship]], {{convert|31|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
The site is a shallow, overgrown lake in the [[Vistula|Vistula Delta]] near the [[Baltic Sea]] coast that was once part of the [[Vistula Lagoon]].<ref name="Ramsar Briefing" /> The lake itself holds a variety of [[Aquatic plants|hydrophilic plants]], including an array of [[nymphaeaceae]], and is surrounded by [[marsh]]es dominated by [[Reed bed|common reed beds]] ({{lang-lat|[[Phragmites]]}}) that transition into [[Wetlands|wooded wetlands]] of black alder ({{lang-lat|Alnus glutinosa}}).<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name="RSP"/>

*''(Site 284)''&nbsp;'''[[Karaś Lake|Karaś Lake Nature Reserve]]''', [[Warmian-Masurian Voivodeship]],{{convert|8|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
The site is a large, shallow [[glacial lake]] typical of those located in the [[Masurian Lake District]].<ref name="PWN">{{cite book | title=Geografia regionalna Polski | publisher=Wydawnictwo Naukowe PWN | author=Kondracki, Jerzy | year=1998 | location=Warsaw | isbn=83-01-12479-2|language=pl}}</ref><ref name="Ramsar Briefing" /> The [[littoral zone]] surrounding the lake provides significant opportunities for wetland bird breeding habitats in the extensive reed beds, [[bog]]s and in the surrounding wetland forests.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name="RSP"/>

*''(Site 1566)''&nbsp;'''[[Karkonosze National Park]]''', [[Lower Silesian Voivodeship]], {{convert|0.4|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
The site consists of three [[subalpine zone]] [[bog]]s along the [[Czech Republic|Czech]] border, in the [[Karkonosze Mountains]].<ref name="Ramsar Briefing" /> The bogs are located at the watershed dividing the [[Baltic Sea]] and [[North Sea]] basins.<ref name="PWN"/><ref name="RSP"/>
The bogs themselves support an extensive [[algae|algal]] community while the surrounding area consists of dwarf [[Mountain pine]] ({{lang-lat|Pinus mugo}}) and low-growth vegetation.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name="RSP"/>

*''(Site 166)''&nbsp;'''[[Łuknajno Lake|Łuknajno Lake Nature Reserve]]''', [[Warmian-Masurian Voivodeship]],{{convert|7|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}, Designated 1977
The site is a [[glacial lake]] typical of those located in the [[Masurian Lake District]] with an area of {{convert|6.8|km2|sqmi}}, and a maximum depth of {{convert|3|m|ft}}.<ref name="PWN"/><ref name="Ramsar Briefing" /><ref>B. Konopka, C. Mazur, S. Starzewski, ''Grosse Masurische Seen. Touristenkarte'', wyd. Copernicus, PPWK Warszawa 2003, {{ISBN|83-7329-245-4}}</ref> The lake is connected with nearby Sniardwy Lake by a channel.<ref>T. Kowalik, P. Świątkowski, T. Cieślik, "Polskie Parki Narodowe i nie tylko ..." Informator Europejskiego Centrum Ekologicznego, Warszawa 1996, {{ISBN|83-906275-5-8}}</ref> The site is a breeding ground for water birds such as [[grebe]], [[water rail]] ({{lang-lat|Rallus aquaticus}}), [[moorhen]], [[grey heron]] ({{lang-lat|Ardea cinerea}}), [[bearded reedling]] ({{lang-lat|Panurus biarmicus}}), [[white-tailed eagle]] ({{lang-lat|Haliaeetus albicilla}}), [[osprey]] ({{lang-lat|Pandion haliaetus}}), rust-coloured [[Kite (bird)|kite]], [[cormorant]] and [[black tern]] ({{lang-lat|Chlidonias niger}}). The lake has been a protected location since 1937 as a habitat of the [[mute swan]] ({{lang-lat|Cygnus olor}}), every year there are a dozen to tens of dozens of nesting pairs, and during [[moulting]] they arrive in numbers reaching up to 2,000 birds.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name="RSP"/><ref name=fauna>{{pl icon}} Ludwik Tomiałojć, Tadeusz Stawarczyk: ''Awifauna Polski. Rozmieszczenie, liczebność i zmiany.'' [[Wrocław]]: PTPP "pro Natura", 2003, pp. 157–297. {{ISBN|83-919626-1-X}}</ref><ref name="biosphere">{{cite web | url=http://www.unesco.org/mabdb/br/brdir/directory/contact.asp?code=POL | title=UNESCO biosphere reserves directory for Poland | publisher=UNESCO | accessdate=13 November 2013}}</ref>

*''(Site 758)''&nbsp;'''[[Milicz Ponds Nature Reserve]]''', [[Lower Silesian Voivodeship]],{{convert|53|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
The site, located within [[Barycz Valley Landscape Park]], consists of various small ponds in the [[Barycz (river)|Barycz River]] valley with a total area of about {{convert|77|km2|sqmi}}.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> The ponds are surrounded by forests, meadows and cultivated areas.<ref name="RSP"/> The ponds provide important spring and autumn migration habitat for a variety of [[Goose|geese]],  [[duck]]s and other waterbirds.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/>

*''(Site 1564)''&nbsp;'''[[Narew National Park]]''', [[Podlaskie Voivodeship]], {{convert|73.5|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
The site is a {{convert|35|km|mi}} section of the [[Narew|Narew River]]. It is a swampy valley with [[moraine]] hills typical of a [[braided river]]. Depending on the season and the level of the water table, several [[Riparian zone|riparian area]] ecosystems are available including [[swamps]], [[Tussock (grass)|tussocks]] with surrounding black alder ({{lang-lat|Alnus glutinosa}}) and white willow ({{lang-lat|Salix alba}}) forested areas.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name="RSP"/>

*''(Site 1565)''&nbsp;'''[[Polesie National Park]]''', [[Lublin Voivodeship]], {{convert|98|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
The site comprises a vast open lowland landscape with a mosaic of swamps, moors, lakes, rivers and forests located between the basins of the [[Bug River|Bug]] and [[Wieprz]] rivers.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> The site is part of the European Ecological Corridor of the Bug River.<ref name="RSP"/> The location supports bird species including [[Bird of prey|raptors]] such as [[lesser spotted eagle]] ({{lang-lat|Aquila pomarina}}), [[hen harrier]] ({{lang-lat|Circus cyaneus}}) and [[Montagu's harrier]] ({{lang-lat|Circus pygargus}}) and birds such as [[aquatic warbler]] ({{lang-lat|Acrocephalus paludicola}}), [[marsh sandpiper]] ({{lang-lat|Tringa stagnatilis}}) and Eurasian cranes ({{lang-lat|[[Grus grus]]}}).<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> The area is considered to be an important crossing point for migratory birds.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> The north-south flyways and east-west flyways of birds meet in the region.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> The areas consists of [[Boreal ecosystem|boreal]] [[Scots pine]] ({{lang-lat|Pinus sylvestris}}) forests, black alder ({{lang-lat|Alnus glutinosa}}) wetland forests, meadows and peatbog ([[raised bog]], [[transitional bog]] and [[fen]]) ecosystems.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name=fauna/><ref name="biosphere"/>

*''(Site 285)''&nbsp;'''[[Seven Island Lake Nature Reserve]]''', [[Warmian-Masurian Voivodeship]],{{convert|10|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
The site consists of Oświn Lake and the surrounding area, located on the border with the [[Kaliningrad Oblast]] (an [[exclave]] of [[Russia]])<ref name="PWN"/><ref>Jezioro Oświn i okolice, Monografia przyrodniczo-kulturowa, Bogucki Wydawnictwo Naukowe, Poznań, 2005. {{ISBN|83-60247-19-6}}</ref> for a total area of approximately {{convert|10|km2|sqmi}}, consisting of about {{convert|3.5|km2|sqmi}} of water, {{convert|6|km2|sqmi}} of [[marshland]] and {{convert|0.5|km2|sqmi}} of wetland forest.<ref>[http://bip.uw.olsztyn.pl/pl/bip/urzad_wojewodzki/wydzialy_i_delegatury/wydzialy/wydzial_srodowiska_i_rolnictwa/wykazy_i_rejestry_dostepne_w_wydziale/px_rejestr__rezerwaty_przyrody.pdf Rejestr rezerwatów przyrody województwa warmińsko-mazurskiego]</ref> It is an important way-station for migratory waterbirds such as [[Goose|geese]] and [[duck]]s.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name="RSP"/>

*''(Site 283)''&nbsp;'''[[Świdwie|Świdwie Nature Reserve]]''', [[West Pomeranian Voivodeship]], {{convert|9.8|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
A freshwater lake in [[Wkrzańska Forest]] near the [[Germany|German]] border.<ref name="PWN"/><ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> The lake is dominated by [[Reed bed|common reed beds]] ({{lang-lat|Phragmites}}) and sedge colonies ({{lang-lat|[[Cyperaceae]]}}) with little open water.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> It is an important way-station for migratory waterbirds such as [[Goose|geese]] and [[duck]]s.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name="RSP"/>

*''(Site 757)''&nbsp;'''[[Słowiński National Park]]''', [[Pomeranian Voivodeship]], {{convert|182|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}, Designated 1995
The site consists of set of [[dunes]], [[brackish]] lakes, bogs, and wetland forests on the southern [[Baltic Sea]] coast between [[Łeba]] and [[Rowy, Pomeranian Voivodeship|Rowy]], Poland.<ref name="PWN"/><ref name="RSP"/> The coastal [[aeolian processes]] have produced some of the most extensive and active mobile sand dunes, which can reach {{convert|30|m|ft|abbr=on}} high, on the Baltic Sea.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> [[Coastal erosion]] and other geo-morphological processes lead to the creation of sand-bars, forming brackish lakes and bogs.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/>
The area consists of a series of vegetation zones going from the sand communities of the coastline towards the forests of the mainland.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> The forest includes beech ({{lang-lat|Fagus sylvatica}}), birch ({{lang-lat|Betula pubescens}}), alder ({{lang-lat|Alnus glutinosa}}), pine and oak. It is an important way station for migrating wader birds and waterbirds such as [[Goose|geese]], [[duck]]s and [[swan]]s.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> The [[white-tailed eagle]] ({{lang-lat|Haliaeetus albicilla}}) and other birds nest at the site.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name=fauna/><ref name="biosphere"/>

*''(Site 282)''&nbsp;'''[[Ujście Warty National Park]]''', [[Lubusz Voivodeship]], {{convert|42|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
The location is an artificial [[reservoir]], at the confluence of the [[Warta]] and [[Oder]] rivers, near the [[Germany|German]] border.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/> The site is set in the [[Warta]] River [[floodplain]] and is surrounded by marshes. It is an important wintering location for migratory waterbirds such as [[Goose|geese]] and [[duck]]s.<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name="RSP"/>

*''(Site 1567)''&nbsp;'''[[Wigry National Park]]''', [[Podlaskie Voivodeship]], {{convert|151|sqkm|sqmi|abbr=on}}
The site is a diverse wetland system around [[Wigry Lake]] and 42 smaller glacial lakes surrounded by [[Boreal ecosystem|boreal]] woodlands.<ref name="RSP"/> The location shelters three globally endangered bird species, [[red kite]] ({{lang-lat|Milvus milvus}}), [[white-tailed eagle]] ({{lang-lat|Haliaeetus albicilla}}) and [[corn crake]] ({{lang-lat|Crex crex}}).<ref name="Ramsar Briefing"/><ref name=fauna/>

